Notes: Environmental Tolerances: Zone 7 is the coldest zone in which winter pea might reliably survive; survival is less certain in Zone 7a than Zone 7b.
Notes: Basic Agronomics: Dry matter highly dependent on planting and termination date and precipitation. Season length, habit vary by cultivar. Biomass breaks down quickly; early planting and termination reduces winter survival. Mixes well with grains when grown for forage. Bloat potential that is easily managed. Seed vigor highly variable. For grazing purposes, restrict to 30% of total ration or mixing with a grass is recommended.
Soil Drainage: ["Somewhat poorly drained","Moderately well drained","Well drained","Excessively drained","Well drained muck"]
Planting green: When planting green into viney crops, wrapping is of concern.  Equipment should be equipped with row cleaners capable or slicing residue and guards to prevent wrapping.  Spoked or posi closing wheels may wrap.
Notes: Termination [Goal: Method: Timing: If using herbicides to terminate use a tank mixture (e.g., glyphosate + dicamba or 2,4-d)
Notes: Weeds: Late planting increases heaving. Weak plant with low volunteer seed survivability.
Notes: Disease & Non-Weed Pests: Information too limited to rate P and K effect. Some cultivars, nematode resistant. Poor host for soybean cyst nematode. With late planting,  biomass is low and spring pea won't suppress winter weeds. Good cool season component for grazing mixes. Quick cool season nitrogen fixer. Susceptible to sclerotinia in East;  Late planting increases heaving. Host for root knot nematode, Penetrans Root-Lesion Nematode and sugarbeet cyst nematode.  Weak plant with low volunteer seed survivability.
Notes: Best mixed with cereals to prevent lodging.
